   <m>{\large \textbf{23.1 Symmetric Matrices}}</m>
   <p><m>{\mathbf{Definitions}}</m>:</p>
   <p>Matrix <m>A</m> is <m>\textbf{symmetric}</m> if it satisfies <m>A = A^T</m>.</p>
   <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
   <p><m>{\textbf{Examples}}</m>:</p>
   <p>In this part of the course we often encounter the expressions</p>
   <me>A^T A, \textup{ }vv^T, \textup{ and } PDP^T</me>
   <p>Which of the following are symmetric matrices?</p>
   <p> <m>\textup{ }</m> <m>\textup{ }</m>1. <m>X = A^T A</m>, where <m>A</m> is a real <m>n \times n</m> matrix.</p>
   <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
   <p> <m>\textup{ }</m> <m>\textup{ }</m>2. <m>Y = vv^T</m>, where <m>v</m> is a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p>
   <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
   <p> <m>\textup{ }</m> <m>\textup{ }</m>3. <m>Z = PDP^T</m>, where <m>D</m> is a diagonal, and <m>P^{-1} = P^T</m>.</p>
   <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
