         <m>{\large \textbf{23.3 The Spectral Decomposition of a Matrix}}</m>
         <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
         <p><m>\large \textup{Spectral Decomposition}</m>:</p>
         <p>Suppose <m>A</m> can be orthogonally diagonalized as</p>
         <me>A = PDP^T = (\vec{u}_1 \cdots \vec{u}_n) \begin{pmatrix} \lambda_1 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\ \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\ 0 \amp \cdots \amp \lambda_n \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} {\vec{u}_1}^T \\ \vdots \\ {\vec{u}_n}^T \end{pmatrix}</me>
         <p>Then <m>A</m> has the decomposition</p>
         <me>A = \lambda_1 \vec{u}_1 {\vec{u}_1}^T + \cdots + \lambda_n \vec{u}_n {\vec{u}_n}^T = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \lambda_i \vec{u}_i {\vec{u}_i}^T</me>
         <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
         <p><m>{\textbf{Example}}</m>:</p>
         <p>Construct a spectral decomposition for <m>A = PDP^T</m>.</p>
         <me>A = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp -5 \\ -5 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix},\textup{ } P = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{pmatrix} -1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}, \textup{ } D = \begin{pmatrix} 6 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -4 \end{pmatrix}</me>
         <p>Leave your expression for <m>A</m> as the sum of two matrices.</p>
    </page>
